  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering, both at the federal and international levels. Here's a breakdown of the key ones:\n\n**United States Federal Statutes:**\n\n*   **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of Monetary Instruments):** This is the primary federal money laundering statute. It prohibits a wide range of activities related to concealing or disguising the nature, location, source, ownership, or control of illegal proceeds. It covers:\n    *   Financial transactions (e.g., deposits, withdrawals, transfers) with the intent to promote unlawful activity, conceal illegal proceeds, or avoid transaction reporting requirements.\n    *   Transportation of monetary instruments or funds into or out of the United States with the intent to promote unlawful activity or conceal illegal proceeds.\n    *   It requires the government to prove intent to promote a specified unlawful activity (SUA), conceal or disguise the nature of the proceeds, or avoid reporting requirements.\n    *   SUAs are listed in 18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956(c)(7), and include a wide range of crimes, such as drug trafficking, fraud, terrorism financing, and many others.\n\n*   **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957 (",
